Hough superior to a tyrant's doom Smile at the menace of the slave of Rome : Each soul whom truth could fire , or virtue move , Each breast , strong panting with its country's love , All that to Albion gave the heart or head , That wisely counselled , or that bravely bled , All , all appear ; on me they grateful smile , The well-earned prise of every virtuous toil To me with fillial reverence they bring , And hang fresh trophies over my honoured spring Ah ! I remember well yonder beachen spray , There Addison first tuned his polished lay ; 'Twas there great Cato's form first met his eye , In all the pomp of freeborn majesty ; " My son , he cried , observe this mien with awe , " In solemn lines the strong resemblance draw ; " The piercing notes shall strike each British ear ; " Each British eye shall drop the patriot tear
Each soul whom truth could fire , or virtue

the bard assenting bowed , The lay to liberty and Cato flowed ; While Echo , as she roved the vale along , Joined the strong cadence of his Roman song

stripped vain falsehood of her gaudy vest ; Here truth's collected beams first filled his mind , Ere long to burst in blessings on mankind
